<td colspan="3" class="boilerplate metadata" style="line-height:10pt; padding:0.5em;"><small><b>Note</b>: This page may contain <a href="/wiki/Help:IPA" title="Help:IPA" class="mw-redirect">IPA</a> phonetic symbols in <a href="/wiki/Unicode" title="Unicode">Unicode</a>.</small></td>
</tr>
</table>
<p><b>Interlingua</b> (<a href="/wiki/ISO_639" title="ISO 639">ISO 639</a> language codes <i>ia</i>, <i>ina</i>) is an <a href="/wiki/International_auxiliary_language" title="International auxiliary language">international auxiliary language</a> (IAL), developed between 1937 and 1951 by the <a href="/wiki/International_Auxiliary_Language_Association" title="International Auxiliary Language Association">International Auxiliary Language Association</a> (IALA). It is the second or third most widely used IAL (after <a href="/wiki/Esperanto" title="Esperanto">Esperanto</a> and perhaps <a href="/wiki/Ido" title="Ido">Ido</a>) and the most widely used <a href="/wiki/International_auxiliary_language#Classification" title="International auxiliary language">naturalistic</a> IAL<sup id="cite_ref-gopsill1990_0-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-gopsill1990-0" title=""><span>[</span>1<span>]</span></a></sup>: in other words, its vocabulary, grammar and other characteristics are largely derived from natural languages. Interlingua was developed to combine a simple, mostly regular grammar<sup id="cite_ref-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-1" title=""><span>[</span>2<span>]</span></a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-2" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-2" title=""><span>[</span>3<span>]</span></a></sup> with a vocabulary common to the widest possible range of languages,<sup id="cite_ref-iala1971_3-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-iala1971-3" title=""><span>[</span>4<span>]</span></a></sup> making it unusually easy to learn, at least for those whose native languages were sources of Interlingua's vocabulary and grammar.<sup id="cite_ref-breinstrup-beginners_4-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-breinstrup-beginners-4" title=""><span>[</span>5<span>]</span></a></sup> Conversely, it is used as a rapid introduction to many natural languages.<sup id="cite_ref-gopsill1990_0-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-gopsill1990-0" title=""><span>[</span>1<span>]</span></a></sup> Interlingua is also unusual for being immediately understandable to hundreds of millions of people<sup id="cite_ref-5" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-5" title=""><span>[</span>6<span>]</span></a></sup> who speak a <a href="/wiki/Romance_language" title="Romance language" class="mw-redirect">Romance language</a>.</p>
